<p>Marbella apartments — whether in Nueva Andalucía, Los Boliches, La Cañada, Puerto Banús or the Golden Mile — share a common challenge: the terrace. Too windy in spring, too hot in summer afternoons, and a little cool on winter evenings. <strong>The right terrace enclosure turns those 6 months of reluctant use into 12 months of enjoyment.</strong> Here's what works best and why.</p>

<h2>The Marbella terrace challenge</h2>

<p>Marbella's climate is one of the best in Europe — 320+ sunny days per year, mild winters, warm summers. But the reality for terrace owners is more nuanced:</p>

<ul>
  <li><strong>Levante wind:</strong> The east wind hits periodically from spring through autumn and can make a terrace unusable in minutes</li>
  <li><strong>Western sun exposure:</strong> Many apartments with sea views face southwest, getting intense afternoon sun from May to October</li>
  <li><strong>Evening temperature drops:</strong> October to April evenings drop to 8–14°C, too cold for comfortable outdoor dining without a heater</li>
  <li><strong>Saline air:</strong> Close to the sea, salt air corrodes anything that isn't marine-grade stainless or powder-coated aluminium</li>
</ul>

<h2>Option 1: Frameless glass curtains — the Marbella favourite</h2>

<p>Frameless glass curtains are by far the most popular terrace enclosure in Marbella. And for good reason: they solve the wind and temperature problems without obstructing the views that justify the property price in the first place.</p>

<p>The panels fold completely to one side on sunny days, leaving the terrace 100% open. On windy or cool evenings, close them in 30 seconds. They're practically invisible from outside, which makes them easy to approve in communities of owners.</p>

<p><strong>Best for:</strong> Apartments with sea or golf views, properties where aesthetics are paramount, holiday rental properties.<br>
<strong>Price range:</strong> €250–€500 per linear metre installed. Typical Marbella apartment: €1,200–€3,500 complete.</p>

<h2>Option 2: Semi-framed glass systems</h2>

<p>Glass panels with a slim aluminium perimeter frame. Better sealed against driving rain and slightly more rigid in very strong winds. The frames are visible but slim — not as clean as frameless but noticeably more weather-resistant.</p>

<p><strong>Best for:</strong> Apartments facing directly into the sea breeze, higher floors where wind loads are greater.<br>
<strong>Price range:</strong> €320–€580 per linear metre.</p>

<h2>Option 3: Bioclimatic pergola (for ground floor, villas, private gardens)</h2>

<p>If you have a ground-floor apartment with a private garden, a corner terrace, or a villa — a bioclimatic pergola is worth considering. The motorised louvres control sunlight and create a sheltered outdoor room usable year-round. Add zip screen sides for full wind protection.</p>

<p><strong>Best for:</strong> Ground-floor apartments with private terraces, villas, townhouses with large private outdoor areas.<br>
<strong>Price range:</strong> €10,000–€40,000 depending on size and configuration.</p>

<h2>What about the community of owners?</h2>

<p>Almost every apartment in Marbella is in a community of owners, and you'll need their vote to install an enclosure. The good news: frameless glass curtains are the easiest system to get approved because they're reversible (no permanent changes to the building) and nearly invisible from the street. We've helped hundreds of Marbella property owners navigate this process — read our guide on <a href="/en/terrace-enclosures-spain">terrace enclosures in Spain: the legal side</a>.</p>

